  "origin": {
    "question": "19.38 In cosmology one usually uses coordinates comoving with the galaxies. Let $(r, x^i)$ be such a system, and let the metric take the general form\\n$$\\n\\\\\\\\mathrm {d s}^{2} = - \\\\\\\\mathrm {d} \\\\\\\\tau^{2} + 2 \\\\\\\\mathrm {g}_{0 \\\\\\\\mathrm {i}} \\\\\\\\mathrm {d} \\\\\\\\tau \\\\\\\\mathrm {d x}^{\\\\\\\\mathrm {i}} + \\\\\\\\mathrm {g}_{\\\\\\\\mathrm {i j}} \\\\\\\\mathrm {d x}^{\\\\\\\\mathrm {i}} \\\\\\\\mathrm {d x}^{\\\\\\\\mathrm {j}}\\n$$\\nwhere $\\mathbf{g}_{0\\\\\\\\mathrm{i}}$ and $\\mathbf{g}_{\\\\\\\\mathrm {ij}}$ can be functions of $\\pmb{\\\\\\\\tau}$ and $\\mathbf{x}^{\\\\\\\\mathrm {i}}$ . Show (f) that $\\mathbf{g}_{0\\\\\\\\mathbf{i},0} = 0$ if and only if galaxies fall on geodesics;",
    "answer": "$g_{0i,0} = 0$",
